  sodium: 0.9 g
  serving size: 624
author: Mimi Morley
course: main course
servings: 2
---

Preheat your oven to 200°C. Chop the @potatoes{2} into 2cm wide wedges (no need to peel). Pop them on a large #baking tray{} and drizzle over some @oil{}. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Spread out in a single layer, then roast on the top shelf of your oven until golden on the outside and soft in the middle, ~{25-30%minutes}. Turn halfway through cooking.

Meanwhile, finely chop the @flat leaf parsley{1}(finely chopped) (stalks and all!). Halve the @red chilli{1} lengthways, deseed and finely chop. Halve, peel and finely chop the @echalion shallot{1}(finely chopped). Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Put the shallot, garlic, @dried oregano{1}, half the parsley and half the chilli in a large #bowl{}. Add the @panko breadcrumbs{10}, @British beef mince{240%g} and @water{2}(tbsp). Season with salt and pepper. Mix with your hands and shape into burgers about 2cm thick, 1 per person.

> IMPORTANT: Remember to wash your hands after handling raw meat!

Heat a drizzle of oil in a #frying pan{} on medium-high heat. Once hot, add the burgers and fry until browned on the outside and cooked through, ~{12-14%minutes} in total. Carefully turn them every ~{4%minutes} and lower the heat if they are burning.

> IMPORTANT: The burgers are cooked when they are no longer pink in the middle.

While the burgers cook, halve the @baby plum tomatoes{125} and pop them in a bowl. Add the remaining parsley and chilli along with the @red wine vinegar{12}(tbsp) and @olive oil{2}(tbsp). Season with salt and pepper and mix together. Halve the @burger buns{2}. A couple of minutes before the wedges are cooked, put the buns in your oven to warm through.

When everything is ready, spread some @mayonnaise{2} on the bottom of each bun, add the burger followed by the top of the bun. Serve with the potato wedges and tomato salad. Enjoy!